ww.flickr.com/photos/akinyc/sets/72057594053063859/ January 2006 images of Trotsky House, Mexico City]\n* [http://www.marxist.com/LeninAndTrotsky/ Lenin and Trotsky\u2014 What they Really Stood For] by [[Alan Woods (politician)|Alan Woods]] and [[Ted Grant]]\n* [http://libcom.org/library/contradiction-trotsky-claude-lefort ''The Contradiction of Trotsky''] by [[Claude Lefort]]\n* [http://www.marxists.org/archive/trotsky/index.htm The Leon Trotsky Internet Archive] at [[Marxists.org]] (under [[GFDL|GNU Free Documentation License]])\n* [http://fora.tv/2009/07/28/Uncommon_Knowledge_Christopher_Hitchens__Robert_Service] ''Uncommon Knowledge'' Interview with [[Christopher Hitchens]] and [[Robert Service (historian)|Robert Service]] on Leon Trotsky\n* [http://jewishhistorylectures.org/2012/04/26/leon-trotsky-jews-on-the-left/ Leon Trotsky: Jews on the Left, Video Lecture by Dr. [[Henry Abramson]]]\n* [http://hdl.handle.net/10622/ARCH01483 Lev Davidovi\u010d Trockij / International Left Opposition Archives] at the [[International Institute of Social History]]\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/017601}}\n* [https://libcom.org/library/the-bolsheviks-and-workers-control-solidarity-group] An historical presentation of the party state that replaced the soviets.\n\n===Works===\n*{{marxists.org|trotsky|Leon Trotsky}}\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=Trotsky,+Leon | name=Leon Trotsky}}\n* {{FadedPage|id=Trotsky, Leon|name=Leon Trotsky|author=yes}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Leon Trotsky}}\n* {{Librivox author |id=4200}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mikhail Tereshchenko]]<br />(Minister of Foreign Affairs)}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Foreign Minister of Russia|People's Commissar for Foreign Affairs]]|years=1917\u20131918}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Georgy Chicherin]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Nikolai Podvoisky]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Defence of Soviet Union|People's Commissar for Army and Navy Affairs]]|years=1918\u20131925}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mikhail Frunze]]}}\n{{S-ach}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Winston Churchill]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[List of people on the cover of Time Magazine: 1920s|Cover of Time Magazine]]\n|years=18 May 1925}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Thomas A. Edison]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Newton D. Baker]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[List of people on the cover of Time Magazine: 1920s|Cover of Time Magazine]]\n|years=21 Nov 1927}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Frank Orren Lowden]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[William S. Knudsen]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[List of people on the cover of Time Magazine: 1930s|Cover of Time Magazine]]\n|years=25 Jan 1937}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Thomas E. Dewey]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Leon Trotsky|state=expanded}}\n{{Russian Revolution 1917}}\n{{Soviet dissidents}}\n{{Foreign ministers of Russia and the Soviet Union}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trotsky, Leon}}\n[[Category:Leon Trotsky| ]]\n[[Category:1879 births]]\n[[Category:1940 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bobrynets Raion]]\n[[Category:People from Yelisavetgradsky Uyezd]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian atheists]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian historians]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian Jews]]\n[[Category:Old Bolsheviks]]\n[[Category:Trotskyists|*]]\n[[Category:Anti-fascists]]\n[[Category:Anti-capitalists]]\n[[Category:Russian anti\u2013World War I activists]]\n[[Category:Assassinated Jews]]\n[[Category:Russian atheism activists]]\n[[Category:Russian autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Russian historians]]\n[[Category:Russian communists]]\n[[Category:Russian socialists]]\n[[Category:Russian Marxists]]\n[[Category:Russian revolutionaries]]\n[[Category:Comintern people]]\n[[Category:Politburo of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union members]]\n[[Category:Communist writers]]\n[[Category:Expelled members of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of Russia]]\n[[Category:Jewish atheists]]\n[[Category:Jewish Mexican history]]\n[[Category:Jewish socialists]]\n[[Category:Historians of communism]]\n[[Category:Soviet Marxist historians]]\n[[Category:20th-century historians]]\n[[Category:Marxist theorists]]\n[[Category:Marxist writers]]\n[[Category:Orthodox Marxists]]\n[[Category:People excommunicated by synagogues]]\n[[Category:People of the 1905 Russian Revolution]]\n[[Category:People of the Russian Revolution]]\n[[Category:People of the Russian Civil War]]\n[[Category:Treaty of Brest-Litovsk]]\n[[Category:People's Commissars and Ministers of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Red Banner]]\n[[Category:Russian expatriates in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Russian expatriates in Norway]]\n[[Category:Refugees in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Refugees in Norway]]\n[[Category:Soviet expellees]]\n[[Category:Jewish Soviet politicians]]\n[[Category:Soviet Ministers of Defence]]\n[[Category:Nonpersons in the Eastern Bloc]]\n[[Category:Mensheviks]]\n[[Category:Soviet Trotskyists]]\n[[Category:Russian Social Democratic Labour Party members]]\n[[Category:20th-century Russian writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century atheists]]\n[[Category:War correspondents of the Balkan Wars]]\n[[Category:People with epilepsy]]\n[[Category:Assassinated Soviet people]]\n[[Category:Assassinated Russian politicians]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Deaths by stabbing in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Ashkenazi Jews]]\n[[Category:People of the Polish\u2013Soviet War]]\n[[Category:People forcibly stripped of Soviet citizenship]]\n[[Category:Soviet emigrants to Mexico]]\n[[Category:Soviet emigrants to Turkey]]\n[[Category:Soviet emigrants to France]]\n[[Category:Soviet emigrants to Norway]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to France]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to Spain]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Imperial Russian emigrants to Austria-Hungary]]\n[[Category:Contributors to the Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]\n[[Category:Russian atheist writers]]\n[[Category:Murdered male writers]]\n[[Category:Murdered philosophers]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian philosophers]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian people murdered abroad]]\n[[Category:Russian people murdered abroad]]\n[[Category:Anti-Stalinist left]]\n[[Category:Soviet people murdered abroad]]\n[[Category:People killed in Soviet intelligence operations]]\n[[Category:Jewish anti-fascists]]\n[[Category:Russian anti-fascists]]\n[[Category:Russian exiles]]\n[[Category:1940s murders in Mexico]]\n[[Category:1940 crimes in Mexico]]\n[[Category:1940 murders in North America]]\n", "name_user": "Koneke", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAssassination:Remove broken link (would fix it instead, but not sure what the proper page to point it to is). Removed a double space.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leon_Trotsky"}
{"title_page": "National Registry of the Historic Hotels of America", "text_new": "{{dablinks|date=April 2020}}\n<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Historic Hotels of America|2=Talk:National Registry of the Historic Hotels of America#Requested move 14 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{uc|date=April 2020}}\nThis is a list of hotels affiliated with the [[National Trust for Historic Preservation#Historic Hotels of America|Historic Hotels of America]] (HHA), a program of the [[National Trust for Historic Preservation]] that was founded in 1989.<ref name=hha/>  It is intended to be a complete listing of HHA's nation-wide registry.\n\n[[File:Willard Hotel from Pershing Park2.jpg|thumb|upright|The [[Willard Hotel]] in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite web|title=Willard Hotel|url=http://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/the-willard-intercontinental-washington-dc|website=historichotels.org|publisher=Historic Hotels of America|accessdate=December 12, 2014}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Caribbean Motel NJ.JPG|thumb|The [[Caribbean Motel]] in [[Wildwood Crest, New Jersey]], listed in the [[National Register of Historic Places]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Caribbean Motel|url=http://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/caribbean-motel|website=historichotels.org|publisher=Historic Hotels of America|accessdate=December 12, 2014}}</ref>]]\nThe National Trust for Historic Preservation created the HHA program in 1989, with 32 charter members,<ref name=\"hha\"/> listed below. HHA accepts nominations and identifies hotels that have maintained their authenticity, sense of place, and architectural integrity. As of June 5, 2015, the program/registry included over 260 members in 44 states, including the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, and the U.S. Virgin Islands.<ref name=hha>{{cite web|title=About Historic Hotels of America|url=http://www.historichotels.org/about-historic-hotels/|website=Historic Hotels of America|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nTo be included in the program, hotels must be at least 50 years old; designated by the U.S. Secretary of the Interior as a [[National Historic Landmark]] or listed in or eligible for listing in the [[National Register of Historic Places]];<ref name=NRA>{{cite web|title=National Register of Historic Places|url=http://www.nps.gov/nr/|website=nps.gov/nr|accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> and recognized as having historic significance.\n\nThe program generates funds for the National Trust via any bookings of the hotels done through the HistoricHotels.org website,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mydigitalpublication.com/publication/?m=45025&i=571104&view=articleBrowser&article_id=3322041 |title=Lawrence P. Horwitz statement}}</ref> other financial connections may exist and are to be clarified.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nIts charter members included:\n*[[Fairmont Copley Plaza]] (1912), Boston, Massachusetts\n*[[Hotel duPont]] (1903), Wilmington, Delaware\n*[[John Rutledge House]] (1763), Charleston, South Carolina\n*[[Kings Courtyard Inn]] (1853), Charleston, South Carolina\n*[[La Valencia Hotel]] (1926), La Jolla, California\n[[File:Moanahotel hawaii.jpg|right|thumb|Moana Surfrider]]\n*[[Moana Surfrider]] (1901), the first hotel on [[Waikiki]], [[Honolulu]], Hawaii \n*[[Morrison-Clark Historic Inn]] (1864), Washington, D.C.\n*[[Omni Bretton Arms Inn]], Bretton Woods, New Hampshire (1896), [[Mount Washington Hotel]]\n*[[Omni Mount Washington Resort]], Bretton Woods, New Hampshire (1902), [[Mount Washington Hotel]]\n*[[Strater Hotel]] (1887), Durango, Colorado\n*[[Admiral Hotel (Mobile, Alabama)|The Admiral Hotel]] (1940), Mobile, Alabama\n*[[The Bellevue-Stratford Hotel|The Bellevue Hotel]] (1904), Philadelphia, Pennsylvania \n*[[The Broadmoor]] (1918), Colorado Springs, Colorado\n*[[Brown Hotel (Louisville, Kentucky)|The Brown Hotel]] (1923), Louisville, Kentucky\n[[File:Don Cesar.jpg|right|thumb|The Don CeSar]]\n*[[The Don CeSar]] (1928), St. Pete Beach, Florida\n*[[The Menger Hotel]] (1859), San Antonio, Texas\n*[[Jefferson Hotel (Richmond, Virginia)|The Jefferson Hotel]] (1895), Richmond, Virginia \n*[[The Martha Washington Inn & Spa]] (1832), \n[[File:Mayflower Hotel in Washington, D.C. (Front Entrance).jpg|right|thumb|Mayflower Hotel]]\n*[[The Mayflower Hotel]], [[Autograph Collection]] (1925), Washington, D.C., the oldest operating hotel in D.C.\n*[[The Omni Homestead Resort]] (1766), Hot Springs, Virginia \n*[[Red Lion Inn (Stockbridge)|The Red Lion Inn]] (1773), [[Stockbridge, Massachusetts]], and \n[[File:FDR-Dedicating-Timberline-Lodge-1937.jpg|right|thumb|Timberline Lodge dedication, 1937]]\n*[[Timberline Lodge]] (1937), [[Mount Hood]], Oregon.<ref name=hha/>\n\n{{Horizontal TOC|nonum=y}}\n\nBy state (with repetition of founding ones):\n\n==Alabama==\n*founding: [[Admiral Hotel (Mobile, Alabama)|The Admiral Hotel]] (1940), Mobile, Alabama\n*[[Redmont Hotel]] (1925), Birmingham, Alabama\n*[[Battle House Hotel]] (1852), Mobile, Alabama\n*[[Grand Hotel Golf Resort & Spa]] (1847), [[Point Clear, Alabama]]<ref>[https://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/grand-hotel-golf-resort-spa/]</ref>\n\n==Alaska==\n*[[Hotel Captain Cook]] (1964), Anchorage, Alaska<ref>[https://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/hotel-captain-cook/]</ref>\n\n==Arizona==\n*[[Bright Angel Lodge & Cabins]] (1935), Grand Canyon, Arizona\n*[[El Tovar Hotel]] (1905), Arizona\n*[[Phantom Ranch]] (1922), Grand Canyon, Arizona\n*[[The Wigwam (Litchfield Park, Arizona)|The Wigwam]] (1929), Litchfield Park, Arizona\n*[[Hotel San Carlos]] (1886), Phoenix, Arizona\n*[[Royal Palms Resort and Spa]] (1948), Phoenix, Arizona\n*[[Hassayampa Inn]] (1927), Prescott, Arizona\n*[[Hotel Valley Ho]] (1956), Scottsdale, Arizona\n*[[Tubac Golf Resort and Spa]] (1959), Tubac, Arizona\n*[[Hacienda Del Sol Guest Ranch Resort]] (1929), Tucson, Arizona\n*[[The Hotel Congress]] (1919), Tucson, Arizona.  Where [[John Dillinger]] was captured.\n*[[White Stallion Ranch]] (1900), Tucson, Arizona.  A [[dude ranch]].\n\n==Arkansas==\n*[[1886 Crescent Hotel & Spa]] (1886), Eureka Springs, Arkansas\n*[[Capital Hotel (Little Rock, Arkansas)|Capital Hotel]] (1870), Little Rock, Arkansas\n\n==California==\n*founding: [[La Valencia Hotel]] (1926), La Jolla, California\n*[[Sofia Hotel]] (1926), San Diego, California\n*[[Omni La Casta Resort & Spa]], Carlsbad, California\n*[[The Mission Inn Hotel & Spa|Mission Inn Hotel & Spa]] (1876), Riverside, California. A [[National Historic Landmark]].\n*[[Hotel Casa del Mar]] (1926), Santa Monica, California\n*[[The Hollywood Roosevelt]], Los Angeles, California\n*[[Hotel Constance Pasadena]], Pasadena, California\n*[[Ojai Valley Inn]], Ojai, California\n*[[The Inn at Death Valley]] (1927), California\n*[[Stonepine Estate]] (1920), Carmel, California\n*[[Hayes Mansion]] (1905), San Jose, California\n*[[Claremont Club & Spa]] (1915), Berkeley, California<ref>[https://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/claremont-club-and-spa-a-fairmont-hotel/]</ref> (a Fairmont hotel). Try [[Claremont Club]].\n*[[Berkeley City Club]] (1929), Berkeley, California, built as a women's club.  Designed by [[Julia Morgan]].\n*[[Hotel Whitcomb]] (1916), San Francisco, California\n*[[Palace Hotel, San Francisco|Palace Hotel]], San Francisco, California\n*[[Omni San Francisco Hotel]] (1926-27), San Francisco, California, was built as the [[Finance Center Building]], \"designed by architect [[Frederick H. Meyer]] in collaboration with [[Albin R. Johnson]]\" \n*[[Intercontinental Mark Hopkins Hotel]], San Francisco, California\n*[[Huntington Hotel (San Francisco)|The Huntington Hotel]] (1924), San Francisco, California\n*[[Fairmont Heritage Place, Ghirardelli Square]] (1893), San Francisco, California. Includes NRHP-listed portions: clocktower. Shows as redlink [[Fairmont Heritage Place]] in [[Ghirardelli Square]] article.\n*[[Inn at the Presidio]] (1903), San Francisco, California, originally Pershing Hall Bachelor Officers\u2019 Quarters.\n*[[The Lodge at the Presidio]], San Francisco, California\n*[[Cavallo Point]], in Marin County, not really San Francisco\n*[[Napa River Inn]] (), Napa, California\n*[[Fairmont Sonoma Mission Inn & Spa]] (), Sonoma, California\n*[[Hotel La Rose]] (), Santa Rosa, California\n*[[The Fairmont Hotel San Francisco]]<ref>[https://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/the-fairmont-hotel-san-francisco/]</ref>\n*[[Benbow Inn]] (1926), Garberville, California\n\nAlso, the [[Hotel del Coronado]], in Coronado, California, a U.S. [[National Historic Landmark]] and listed on the NRHP, became a member of the program in 2017,<ref name=add20>{{cite news|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20180111005587/en/20-Legendary-Historic-Hotels-Inducted-Historic-Hotels |title=20 Legendary Historic Hotels Inducted into Historic Hotels of America |date=January 11, 2018 |accessdate=April 14, 2020 |publisher=BusinessWire}} (apparently a press release)</ref>\nbut in 2020 no longer is listed as a member.<ref>[https://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/results.php?search=rezconsole&advanced=Coronado&mon=198154-A1 search yielding no \"Coronado\"] Specific announcement of its withdrawal from program wanted.</ref>\n\n==Colorado==\n*founding: [[Strater Hotel]] (1887), Durango, Colorado\n*founding: [[The Broadmoor]] (1918), Colorado Springs, Colorado\n*[[Hotel Boulderado]] (1909), Boulder, Colorado\n*[[The Cliff House at Pikes Peak]] (1874), Manitou Springs, Colorado\n\nAlso, seemingly, former HHA (included in category), is:\n*[[Stanley Hotel]], Estes Park, Colorado, (added [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=The_Stanley_Hotel&diff=prev&oldid=860102025 here])\n\n==Connecticut==\n*[[The Spa at Norwich Inn]] (1929), Norwich, Connecticut.  try [[Norwich Inn]]. Colonial Revival.\n*[[Water's Edge Resort and Spa]] (1920s), Westbrook, Connecticut. \"Originating from the vision of humanitarian [[Bill Hahn]], the resort has jovial beginnings.\"\n\n==Delaware==\n*founding: [[Hotel duPont]] (1903), Wilmington, Delaware, within [[DuPont Building]]\n*[[The Inn at Montchanin Village]] (1799), Montchanin, Delaware. \"in Delaware's [[Brandywine Valley]]; the inn is, in reality, a restored 19th-century hamlet with 28 guest rooms spread across 11 carefully restored buildings accessible via a maze of ornate gardens.\"\n\n==Florida==\n*founding: [[The Don CeSar]] (1928), St. Pete Beach, Florida. \"Instantly known as Florida's Pink Castle when it opened back in 1928, this ten-story hotel sits on the sugary sands of [[St. Pete Beach]], an island in the Gulf of Mexico.\" Moorish Revival.\n*[[Belleview Inn]] (1897), Belleair, Florida.  [[Henry Plant]], \"a railroad and steamship entrepreneur in 19th century who realized that his passengers would need somewhere to stay. Plant built a grand, Queen Anne-style Victorian hotel...\"\n*[[The Gasparilla Inn & Club]] (1913), Boca Grande, Florida. Classic Revival.\n*[[Colony Hotel & Cabana Club]] (1926), Delray Beach, Florida. \"calls to mind the romantic Flagler era of Florida Mediterranean architecture: three bright yellow stories topped by twin domed towers that echo the color of the historic building's striped awnings. The Colony Porch Bar and retail store fronts are located on Atlantic Avenue. The guestroom windows are sheltered from the Florida sun by colorful yellow-and-red awnings.\" Spanish Colonial Revival.\n*[[Casa Marina Hotel and Restaurant]] (1925), Jacksonville Beach, Florida. Spanish Colonial Revival.\n*[[La Concha Hotel & Spa]] (1926), Key West, Florida.  Try [[La Concha Hotel]]. Colonial - Colonial Revival.\n*[[The Terrace Hotel]] (1924), Lakeland, Florida. \"The [[Terrace Hotel]] opened in 1924 on the site of the previous [[Tremont Hotel]], which had stood for almost forty years.\" Renaissance Revival.\n*[[Casa Faena]] (1928), Miami Beach, Florida. \"[[Casa Claridge's]] is one of the best-kept secrets of Miami's famous South Beach. Its grand Mediterranean architecture, unique interior atrium lobby, and ideal location across from the pristine waters of South Beach, together create the ultimate getaway spot.\" Spanish Colonial Revival.\n*[[Greystone Miami Beach]] (1939), Miami Beach, Florida.  \"designed by renowned architect [[Henry Hohauser]], who was given the title of \u201cGreat Floridian\u201d by Florida\u2019s Department of State in 1993 for his major contribution to the distinct Art Deco architectural scene present throughout the region.\" Art Deco.\n*[[The National Hotel]] (1940), Miami Beach, Florida.  [[National Hotel Miami Beach]], \"an authentically restored Art Deco landmark that epitomizes the mood and decor of the 1940's, redefined with a modern panache. Designed by [[Roy France]], one of the period's foremost architects, National Hotel was one of the grandest luxury hotels on Miami Beach when it opened in 1940.\" Art Deco.\n*[[Casa Monica Resort & Spa]] (1888), St. Augustine, Florida. Moorish Revival.\n*[[The Vinoy Renaissance St. Petersburg Resort & Golf Club]] (1925), St. Petersburg, Florida.  Try [[St. Petersburg Resort & Golf Club]], [[St. Petersburg Resort]]. \"The salmon-colored Mediterranean Revival building opened in 1925 and has overlooked Tampa Bay ever since.\" Mediterranean Revival.\n*[[The Lodge at Wakulla Springs]] (1937), Wakulla Springs, Florida. Built in 1937 by industrialist [[Edward Ball (businessman)|Edward Ball]].\n\nApparently former HHAs (were in category) are: \n*[[Casa Marina Hotel]], Jacksonville Beach, Florida\n*[[Casa Monica Hotel]], St. Augustine, Florida\n*[[La Concha Hotel]], Key West, Florida\n*[[Vinoy Park Hotel]], St. Petersburg, Florida\n\n==Georgia==\n*[[The Candler Hotel Atlanta, Curio Collection by Hilton]] (1904), Atlanta, Georgia  Try [[Candler Hotel]], [[The Candler Hotel]].\n*[[The Georgian Terrace]] (1911), Atlanta, Georgia.  Try [[Georgian Terrace]]. [[Gone With The Wind]]-related, in [[Fox Theater Historic District]].\n*[[The Partridge Inn]] (1910), Augusta, Georgia. Try [[Partridge Inn]]\n*[[Greyfield Inn]] (1900), [[Cumberland Island]], Georgia. Try [[The Greyfield Inn]]\n*[[Jekyll Island Club Resort]] (1887), [[Jekyll Island]], Georgia. Try [[Jekyll Island Club]].\n*[[River Street Inn]] (1817), [[Savannah, Georgia]]. Try [[]]\n*[[The Cotton Sail Hotel]] (1852), Savannah, Georgia. Try [[Cotton Sail Hotel]]\n*[[The King and Prince Beach and Golf Resort]] (1935), [[St. Simons Island]], Georgia. Try [[King and Prince Resort]].\n*[[The DeSoto]] (1890), Savannah, Georgia.  In one of largest historic landmark districts.\n\n==Hawaii==\n*[[Grand Naniloa Hotel]] (1939), Hilo, Hawaii\n*[[Mauna Kea Beach Hotel]] (), Kohala Coast, Hawaii \n*[[Hilton Hawaiian Village]]/[[Waikiki Beach Resort]] (1957), Honolulu, Oahu, Hawaii\n*[[The Royal Hawaiian]] (1927), Honolulu, Oahu, Hawaii\n*[[Pioneer Inn]] (1901), Maui, Hawaii\n*One of the founding ones: [[Moana Surfrider]] (1901), the first hotel on [[Waikiki]], [[Honolulu]], Hawaii \n\n==Illinois==\n*[[Hilton Chicago]] (1927), Chicago, Illinois. Beaux Arts.\n*[[InterContinental Chicago Magnificent Mile]] (), Chicago, Illinois.  Built \"in 1929 as the [[Medinah Athletic Club]], a luxury men's club for members of the Shrine organization.\" Art Deco.\n*[[LondonHouse Chicago]] (), Chicago, Illinois.  Or [[LondonHouse Chicago, Curio Collection by Hilton]]. Beaux Arts.\n*[[Palmer House, A Hilton Hotel]] (), Chicago, Illinois. Remodeled in 2004. Beaux Arts\n*[[Drake Hotel (Chicago)|The Drake Hotel]] (), Chicago, Illinois. Italian Renaissance.\n*[[The Silversmith Hotel]] (), Chicago, Illinois. Arts & Crafts.\n*[[Hilton Orrington/Evanston]] (), Evanston, Illinois\n\n==Indiana==\n*[[The Sherman (Batesville, Indiana)|The Sherman]] (), Batesville, Indiana. \"in the heart of historic downtown Batesville, a convenient midway meeting point between Indianapolis and Cincinnati, The Sherman is a well-loved locale for the people of the town and an important Indiana landmark.\" Tudor Style.\n*[[French Lick Springs Hotel]] (), French Lick, Indiana.  Was built as [[French Lick Resort Casino]]?  \"For over two centuries the [[P