illion dollar renovation finished in 2007\". Try [[Hotel Viking]], [[Viking Hotel]].\n\n==South Carolina==\n*[[Francis Marion Hotel]] (1924), Charleston, South Carolina\n*founding: [[John Rutledge House Inn]] (1763), Charleston, South Carolina\n*founding: [[Kings Courtyard Inn]] (1853), Charleston, South Carolina\n*[[The Dewberry]] (1964-65), Charleston, South Carolina.  [[Mid-century modern]] building, originally the [[L. Mendel Rivers Federal Building]], in the [[Charleston Historic District]].\n*[[Wentworth Mansion]] (1886), Charleston, South Carolina, [[Second Empire architecture|Second Empire]] in style, in the [[Charleston Historic District]].\n*[[The Westin Poinsett]] (1925), Greenville, South Carolina\n\n==South Dakota==\n*[[Hotel Alex Johnson]] (), Rapid City, South Dakota\n*[[Hotel on Phillips]] (), Sioux Falls, South Dakota\n\n==Tennessee==\n*[[The Peabody Memphis]], Memphis, Tennessee \n*[[General Morgan Inn & Conference Center]] (1884), Greeneville, Tennessee, aka [[The General Morgan Inn and Conference Center]].  Where [[John Hunt Morgan]] was shot and fell.  Per NRHP doc, [[General Morgan Inn]] was the [[Hotel Brumley]], originally Grand Hotel. Included in [[Greeneville Historic District (Greeneville, Tennessee)]].\n*[[21c Museum Hotel Nashville by MGallery]] (1900), Nashville, Tennessee.  In downtown Nashville, in the historic [[Gray & Dudley Building]]. \"The group hired the local firm, [[Thompson, Gibel, & Asmus]], to create the building\u2019s architecture, which they modeled in the likeness of the Chicago Commercial School\u2019s Beaux Arts architectural style.\"  Which is located at \"225 Second Avenue, (building says 222) Gray & Dudley Hardware Co. 1895. Chicago Commercial Style.\" in [https://npgallery.nps.gov/GetAsset/9155cac2-a728-4c11-8975-7d0877c03230/ NRHP doc] of NRHP-listed [[Second Avenue Commercial District]] (currently a redlink)\n*[[Union Station Hotel Nashville, Autograph Collection]], Nashville, Tennessee.  Try [[Union Station Hotel Nashville]].  It must be [[Union Station (Nashville)]], a former [[National Historic Landmark]].\n*[[The Hermitage Hotel]], Nashville, Tennessee.  Claimed to be \"the only remaining grand hotel in Nashville and the only commercial Beaux Arts structure in the state.\" Hardly likely?  Article has the assertion from another source, too.\n \n==Texas==\n*[[Hotel Settles]] (), Big Spring, Texas \n*[[Stagecoach Inn (Salado, Texas)|The Stagecoach Inn]] (1852), Salado, Texas \n*[[The Ashton Hotel]] (), Fort Worth, Texas \n*[[Hilton Fort Worth]] (1921), Fort Worth, Texas.  Originally [[Hotel Texas]]. \n*[[The Statler Hotel & Residences|The Statler]] (), Dallas, Texas \n*[[The Sam Houston Hotel]] (), Houston, Texas \n*[[The Whitehall]] (), Houston, Texas \n*[[Omni La Mansion Del Rio]] (), San Antonio, Texas \n*[[The Crockett Hotel]] (), San Antonio, Texas \n*[[Emily Morgan San Antonio - a DoubleTree by Hilton Hotel]] (1924), San Antonio, Texas\n\n==Utah==\n*[[Zion Lodge]] (), Springdale, Utah\n\n==Vermont==\n*[[Castle Hill Resort and Spa]] (), Cavendish, Vermont.  Try [[Castle Hill Resort]], [[Castle Hill]]. Period Houses and Residences.\n*[[The Middlebury Inn]] (1827?), Middlebury, Vermont.  \"The Inn began as the [[Vermont Hotel]], a brick \"public house\" opened by [[Nathan Wood]]{{dn|date=April 2020}} in 1827. The inn changed hands and became the [[Addison House]] in 1852, and then saw improvements in 1865 at the hands of owner [[Darwin Rider]], who ran a free carriage to all trains and operated a large livery for his guests.\" Federal.\n*[[Basin Harbor]] (), Vergennes, Vermont.  \"When [[Ardelia Beach]], founder of the landmark Basin Harbor...\" on [[Lake Champlain]]. Eclectic.\n*[[Woodstock Inn & Resort]] (), [[Woodstock, Vermont]].  Try [[Woodstock Inn]]. \"embraces the vision of Laurance and Mary Rockefeller\": try [[Laurance Rockefeller]], [[Mary Rockefeller]].\n\n==Virginia==\n*Founding: [[The Omni Homestead Resort]] (1766), Hot Springs, Virginia, formerly The Homestead.\n*Founding: [[The Martha Washington Hotel & Spa]] (1832), Abingdon, Virginia.  [[Martha Washington Inn]].\n*[[Boar's Head Resort]], Charlottesville, Virginia, aka [[Boar\u2019s Head Inn]] [[Boar's Head Inn]]\n*[[The Georges]], Lexington, Virginia in the [[Lexington Historic District (Lexington, Virginia)|Lexington Historic District]]\n*[[The Mimslyn Inn]] (1931), Luray, Virginia.  [[Georgian Revival architecture]]. Included in [[Luray Downtown Historic District]].\n*[[The Virginian Lynchburg, Curio Collection by Hilton]] (1913), Lynchburg, Virginia. Try [[The Virginian Lynchburg]], [[Virginian Lynchburg]].\n*[[Inn at Willow Grove]] (1778), Orange, Virginia.  [[Willow Grove Inn]].\n*Founding: [[Jefferson Hotel (Richmond, Virginia)|The Jefferson Hotel]], Richmond, Virginia\n*[[The Hotel Roanoke & Conference Center, Curio - A Collection by Hilton]] (1882), Roanoke, Virginia. [[Hotel Roanoke]], NRHP-listed.\n*[[Blackburn Inn]] (1828), Staunton, Virginia, built as [[Western State Hospital (Staunton, Virginia)]]\n*[[Stonewall Jackson Hotel & Conference Center]] (1924), Staunton, Virginia  [[Stonewall Jackson Hotel]]\n*[[The Cavalier Virginia Beach, Autograph Collection]], Virginia Beach, Virginia. [[Cavalier Hotel]]. \n*[[Airlie]] (1899), Warrenton, Virginia.  [[Airlie, Virginia]]: '''Airlie''' is a small [[unincorporated community]] in [[Fauquier County, Virginia]] situated between [[US Route 17]] and [[US Route 29]].  The village itself runs along [[Virginia State Route 605 (Fauquier County)|State Route 605]], which is named Airlie Road.  It is home to the [[Airlie Conference Center]] and Harry's Restaurant .  The original post office for Airlie, Va was closed and the building was converted to be part of the meeting facilities in the 1990s.  Airlie is within the [[Warrenton, Virginia|Warrenton]] 20187 [[ZIP Code]].\"\n\"In 1899, Philadelphia native [[Harry C. Groome]] built [[Airlie House]] and named it after a castle in Scotland. The grand Georgian Revival-style structure was featured in 1907 in Home and Garden magazine along with its formal gardens, which are still meticulously maintained to this day. / Airlie House met tragedy in 1924 as it was destroyed in a fire. Groome rebuilt the house on its original foundation, but reduced it from three to two stories. / When Dr. Head purchased Airlie Farm in 1956, he laid down the foundation for the course of the structure for the next 50 years. Dr. Head had a vision of creating one of the first conference facilities of its kind in the country. He wanted a place where individuals and organizations could meet in a distraction-free, neutral environment to openly exchange ideas and share opinions on important matters of the day. The purpose, of course, was to ignite thought and inspire collective action. / The development of Dr. Head's vision was a success. He integrated modern meeting facilities and accommodations with the lush, natural setting of the Airlie estate. In 1961, [[Airlie Center]] opened its doors and Life Magazine declared it an innovative \"Island of Thought.\" / With this innovative platform, Dr. Head initiated a variety of programs dedicated to education, environmental research, public health, and social progress. During the Civil Rights Movement, Dr. Head established [[Airlie Center]] as a safe zone for dialogue. [[Airlie Productions]], Dr. Head's studio facilities based at Airlie Center, created hundreds of documentaries on the full spectrum of social and environmental issues and received more than 20 Emmy awards recognizing 20 years of work. / Today, Airlie remains committed to its founding ideals of environmental stewardship and the open exchange of ideas in a distraction-free setting. / Airlie, a member of Historic Hotels of America since 2015, dates back to 1899.\"\n*[[Williamsburg Inn]], Williamsburg, Virginia\n*[[Williamsburg Lodge, Autograph Collection, and Colonial Houses]], Williamsburg, Virginia\n\n==Washington==\n*[[Mayflower Park Hotel]] (1927), Seattle, Washington.  Not found by searching Washington, but in map.<ref>[https://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/mayflower-park-hotel/?from=map]</ref> \n*[[Fairmont Olympic Hotel]] (1924), Seattle, Washington.  Originally the Olympic Hotel. Not found by searching \"Washington\", but in map.<ref>[https://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/fairmont-olympic-hotel/?from=map]</ref>\n\nBut also in category:\n*[[Montvale Hotel]], Spokane, Washington, added by [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Montvale_Hotel&type=revision&diff=864675255&oldid=857757128 this diff], no other info.\n\n==West Virginia==\n*[[Blennerhassett Hotel]], Parkersburg, West Virginia.<ref name=Blennerhassett>{{cite web|title=Blennerhassett Hotel |url=https://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/the-blennerhassett-hotel/ |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Wisconsin==\n*[[American Club (Kohler, Wisconsin)|The American Club]] (1918), Kohler, Wisconsin. [[Walter J. Kohler, Sr.]] founded it.  [[Tudor Revival architecture|Tudor]]-style.\n*[[The Edgewater (Madison, Wisconsin)|The Edgewater]] (1948), Madison, Wisconsin.  Art Deco.\n*[[Hilton Milwaukee City Center]] (1928), Milwaukee, Wisconsin, built as the [[Schroeder Hotel]]\n*[[The Pfister Hotel]] (1893), Milwaukee, Wisconsin.  [[Romanesque Revival architecture|Romanesque Revival]]\n\n==Wyoming==\n*[[Old Faithful Inn]] (), [[Yellowstone National Park]], Wyoming\n*[[Lake Yellowstone Hotel & Cabins]] (), [[Yellowstone National Park]], Wyoming\n*[[Sheridan Inn]] (1892), Sheridan, Wyoming\n*[[Alpenhof Lodge]] (), Teton Village, Wyoming\n*[[The Wort Hotel]] (1941), Jackson, Wyoming\n\n==Washington, D.C.==\n*founding: [[Morrison-Clark Historic Inn]] (1864), Washington, D.C.\n*founding: [[The Mayflower Hotel]] (1925)\n*[[Capital Hilton]] (1943), Washington, District of Columbia\n*[[Georgetown Inn]] (1962), Washington, District of Columbia\n*[[Hotel Lombardy]] (1929), Washington, District of Columbia, converted to a hotel in 1994\n*[[Omni Shoreham Hotel]] (1930), Washington DC\n*[[Phoenix Park Hotel]] (1922), Washington, District of Columbia\n*[[Sofitel Washington DC Lafayette Square]] (1925), Washington, District of Columbia, originally designed in [[Art Deco architecture]] by [[Mihran Mesrobian]]\n*[[The Churchill]] (1906).  Or [[The Churchill Hotel]]?  try [[Churchill Hotel]].  [[Beaux Arts architecture]], orginally a luxury apartment building\n*[[The Fairfax at Embassy Row]] (1927), Washington, District of Columbia. Originally \"The Fairfax Hotel\" or \"Fairfax Hotel\"?\n*[[The Graham Georgetown, Tapestry Collection by Hilton]] (1962), Washington, District of Columbia.  try [[The Graham Georgetown]], [[Graham Hotel]], [[The Graham]].  Formerly [[Hotel Monticello]]. Try [[Monticello Hotel]].\n*[[The Henley Park Hotel]] (1918), Washington, District of Columbia.  Is it named after [[Henley Park]] in Oxfordshire?\n*[[The Willard InterContinental, Washington DC]].  [[Beaux Arts architecture]].\n*[[Washington Hilton]] (1965), Washington, District of Columbia\n\n==Puerto Rico==\n*[[Caribe Hilton]], San Juan, Puerto Rico\n*[[Condado Vanderbilt Hotel]] (1919), San Juan, Puerto Rico\n*[[El Convento Hotel]] (1651), San Juan, Puerto Rico, [[Spanish Colonial architecture]]\n*[[The Condado Plaza Hilton]] (1963), San Juan, Puerto Rico, [[International Style (architecture)|International style]]\n\n==U.S. Virgin Islands==\n*[[The Buccaneer (Christiansted, U.S. Virgin Islands)|The Buccaneer]] (1653), Christiansted, U.S. Virgin Islands\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Hotels]]\n[[Category:Hotel affiliation groups]]\n[[Category:National Trust for Historic Preservation]]\n", "text_old": "{{dablinks|date=April 2020}}\n<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Historic Hotels of America|2=Talk:National Registry of the Historic Hotels of America#Requested move 14 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{uc|date=April 2020}}\nThis is a list of hotels affiliated with the [[National Trust for Historic Preservation#Historic Hotels of America|Historic Hotels of America]] (HHA), a program of the [[National Trust for Historic Preservation]] that was founded in 1989.<ref name=hha/>  It is intended to be a complete listing of HHA's nation-wide registry.\n\n[[File:Willard Hotel from Pershing Park2.jpg|thumb|upright|The [[Willard Hotel]] in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite web|title=Willard Hotel|url=http://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/the-willard-intercontinental-washington-dc|website=historichotels.org|publisher=Historic Hotels of America|accessdate=December 12, 2014}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Caribbean Motel NJ.JPG|thumb|The [[Caribbean Motel]] in [[Wildwood Crest, New Jersey]], listed in the [[National Register of Historic Places]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Caribbean Motel|url=http://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/caribbean-motel|website=historichotels.org|publisher=Historic Hotels of America|accessdate=December 12, 2014}}</ref>]]\nThe National Trust for Historic Preservation created the HHA program in 1989, with 32 charter members,<ref name=\"hha\"/> listed below. HHA accepts nominations and identifies hotels that have maintained their authenticity, sense of place, and architectural integrity. As of June 5, 2015, the program/registry included over 260 members in 44 states, including the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, and the U.S. Virgin Islands.<ref name=hha>{{cite web|title=About Historic Hotels of America|url=http://www.historichotels.org/about-historic-hotels/|website=Historic Hotels of America|accessdate=June 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nTo be included in the program, hotels must be at least 50 years old; designated by the U.S. Secretary of the Interior as a [[National Historic Landmark]] or listed in or eligible for listing in the [[National Register of Historic Places]];<ref name=NRA>{{cite web|title=National Register of Historic Places|url=http://www.nps.gov/nr/|website=nps.gov/nr|accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref> and recognized as having historic significance.\n\nThe program generates funds for the National Trust via any bookings of the hotels done through the HistoricHotels.org website,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mydigitalpublication.com/publication/?m=45025&i=571104&view=articleBrowser&article_id=3322041 |title=Lawrence P. Horwitz statement}}</ref> other financial connections may exist and are to be clarified.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nIts charter members included:\n*[[Fairmont Copley Plaza]] (1912), Boston, Massachusetts\n*[[Hotel duPont]] (1903), Wilmington, Delaware\n*[[John Rutledge House]] (1763), Charleston, South Carolina\n*[[Kings Courtyard Inn]] (1853), Charleston, South Carolina\n*[[La Valencia Hotel]] (1926), La Jolla, California\n[[File:Moanahotel hawaii.jpg|right|thumb|Moana Surfrider]]\n*[[Moana Surfrider]] (1901), the first hotel on [[Waikiki]], [[Honolulu]], Hawaii \n*[[Morrison-Clark Historic Inn]] (1864), Washington, D.C.\n*[[Omni Bretton Arms Inn]], Bretton Woods, New Hampshire (1896), [[Mount Washington Hotel]]\n*[[Omni Mount Washington Resort]], Bretton Woods, New Hampshire (1902), [[Mount Washington Hotel]]\n*[[Strater Hotel]] (1887), Durango, Colorado\n*[[Admiral Hotel (Mobile, Alabama)|The Admiral Hotel]] (1940), Mobile, Alabama\n*[[The Bellevue-Stratford Hotel|The Bellevue Hotel]] (1904), Philadelphia, Pennsylvania \n*[[The Broadmoor]] (1918), Colorado Springs, Colorado\n*[[Brown Hotel (Louisville, Kentucky)|The Brown Hotel]] (1923), Louisville, Kentucky\n[[File:Don Cesar.jpg|right|thumb|The Don CeSar]]\n*[[The Don CeSar]] (1928), St. Pete Beach, Florida\n*[[The Menger Hotel]] (1859), San Antonio, Texas\n*[[Jefferson Hotel (Richmond, Virginia)|The Jefferson Hotel]] (1895), Richmond, Virginia \n*[[The Martha Washington Inn & Spa]] (1832), \n[[File:Mayflower Hotel in Washington, D.C. (Front Entrance).jpg|right|thumb|Mayflower Hotel]]\n*[[The Mayflower Hotel]], [[Autograph Collection]] (1925), Washington, D.C., the oldest operating hotel in D.C.\n*[[The Omni Homestead Resort]] (1766), Hot Springs, Virginia \n*[[Red Lion Inn (Stockbridge)|The Red Lion Inn]] (1773), [[Stockbridge, Massachusetts]], and \n[[File:FDR-Dedicating-Timberline-Lodge-1937.jpg|right|thumb|Timberline Lodge dedication, 1937]]\n*[[Timberline Lodge]] (1937), [[Mount Hood]], Oregon.<ref name=hha/>\n\n{{Horizontal TOC|nonum=y}}\n\nBy state (with repetition of founding ones):\n\n==Alabama==\n*founding: [[Admiral Hotel (Mobile, Alabama)|The Admiral Hotel]] (1940), Mobile, Alabama\n*[[Redmont Hotel]] (1925), Birmingham, Alabama\n*[[Battle House Hotel]] (1852), Mobile, Alabama\n*[[Grand Hotel Golf Resort & Spa]] (1847), [[Point Clear, Alabama]]<ref>[https://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/grand-hotel-golf-resort-spa/]</ref>\n\n==Alaska==\n*[[Hotel Captain Cook]] (1964), Anchorage, Alaska<ref>[https://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/hotel-captain-cook/]</ref>\n\n==Arizona==\n*[[Bright Angel Lodge & Cabins]] (1935), Grand Canyon, Arizona\n*[[El Tovar Hotel]] (1905), Arizona\n*[[Phantom Ranch]] (1922), Grand Canyon, Arizona\n*[[The Wigwam (Litchfield Park, Arizona)|The Wigwam]] (1929), Litchfield Park, Arizona\n*[[Hotel San Carlos]] (1886), Phoenix, Arizona\n*[[Royal Palms Resort and Spa]] (1948), Phoenix, Arizona\n*[[Hassayampa Inn]] (1927), Prescott, Arizona\n*[[Hotel Valley Ho]] (1956), Scottsdale, Arizona\n*[[Tubac Golf Resort and Spa]] (1959), Tubac, Arizona\n*[[Hacienda Del Sol Guest Ranch Resort]] (1929), Tucson, Arizona\n*[[The Hotel Congress]] (1919), Tucson, Arizona.  Where [[John Dillinger]] was captured.\n*[[White Stallion Ranch]] (1900), Tucson, Arizona.  A [[dude ranch]].\n\n==Arkansas==\n*[[1886 Crescent Hotel & Spa]] (1886), Eureka Springs, Arkansas\n*[[Capital Hotel (Little Rock, Arkansas)|Capital Hotel]] (1870), Little Rock, Arkansas\n\n==California==\n*founding: [[La Valencia Hotel]] (1926), La Jolla, California\n*[[Sofia Hotel]] (1926), San Diego, California\n*[[Omni La Casta Resort & Spa]], Carlsbad, California\n*[[The Mission Inn Hotel & Spa|Mission Inn Hotel & Spa]] (1876), Riverside, California. A [[