ntown Historic District]].\n*[[The Virginian Lynchburg, Curio Collection by Hilton]] (1913), Lynchburg, Virginia. Try [[The Virginian Lynchburg]], [[Virginian Lynchburg]].\n*[[Inn at Willow Grove]] (1778), Orange, Virginia.  [[Willow Grove Inn]].\n*Founding: [[Jefferson Hotel (Richmond, Virginia)|The Jefferson Hotel]], Richmond, Virginia\n*[[The Hotel Roanoke & Conference Center, Curio - A Collection by Hilton]] (1882), Roanoke, Virginia. [[Hotel Roanoke]], NRHP-listed.\n*[[Blackburn Inn]] (1828), Staunton, Virginia, built as [[Western State Hospital (Staunton, Virginia)]]\n*[[Stonewall Jackson Hotel & Conference Center]] (1924), Staunton, Virginia  [[Stonewall Jackson Hotel]]\n*[[The Cavalier Virginia Beach, Autograph Collection]], Virginia Beach, Virginia. [[Cavalier Hotel]]. \n*[[Airlie]] (1899), Warrenton, Virginia.  [[Airlie, Virginia]]: '''Airlie''' is a small [[unincorporated community]] in [[Fauquier County, Virginia]] situated between [[US Route 17]] and [[US Route 29]].  The village itself runs along [[Virginia State Route 605 (Fauquier County)|State Route 605]], which is named Airlie Road.  It is home to the [[Airlie Conference Center]] and Harry's Restaurant .  The original post office for Airlie, Va was closed and the building was converted to be part of the meeting facilities in the 1990s.  Airlie is within the [[Warrenton, Virginia|Warrenton]] 20187 [[ZIP Code]].\"\n\"In 1899, Philadelphia native [[Harry C. Groome]] built [[Airlie House]] and named it after a castle in Scotland. The grand Georgian Revival-style structure was featured in 1907 in Home and Garden magazine along with its formal gardens, which are still meticulously maintained to this day. / Airlie House met tragedy in 1924 as it was destroyed in a fire. Groome rebuilt the house on its original foundation, but reduced it from three to two stories. / When Dr. Head purchased Airlie Farm in 1956, he laid down the foundation for the course of the structure for the next 50 years. Dr. Head had a vision of creating one of the first conference facilities of its kind in the country. He wanted a place where individuals and organizations could meet in a distraction-free, neutral environment to openly exchange ideas and share opinions on important matters of the day. The purpose, of course, was to ignite thought and inspire collective action. / The development of Dr. Head's vision was a success. He integrated modern meeting facilities and accommodations with the lush, natural setting of the Airlie estate. In 1961, [[Airlie Center]] opened its doors and Life Magazine declared it an innovative \"Island of Thought.\" / With this innovative platform, Dr. Head initiated a variety of programs dedicated to education, environmental research, public health, and social progress. During the Civil Rights Movement, Dr. Head established [[Airlie Center]] as a safe zone for dialogue. [[Airlie Productions]], Dr. Head's studio facilities based at Airlie Center, created hundreds of documentaries on the full spectrum of social and environmental issues and received more than 20 Emmy awards recognizing 20 years of work. / Today, Airlie remains committed to its founding ideals of environmental stewardship and the open exchange of ideas in a distraction-free setting. / Airlie, a member of Historic Hotels of America since 2015, dates back to 1899.\"\n*[[Williamsburg Inn]], Williamsburg, Virginia\n*[[Williamsburg Lodge, Autograph Collection, and Colonial Houses]], Williamsburg, Virginia\n\n==Washington==\n*[[Mayflower Park Hotel]] (1927), Seattle, Washington.  Not found by searching Washington, but in map.<ref>[https://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/mayflower-park-hotel/?from=map]</ref> \n*[[Fairmont Olympic Hotel]] (1924), Seattle, Washington.  Originally the Olympic Hotel. Not found by searching \"Washington\", but in map.<ref>[https://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/fairmont-olympic-hotel/?from=map]</ref>\n\nBut also in category:\n*[[Montvale Hotel]], Spokane, Washington, added by [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Montvale_Hotel&type=revision&diff=864675255&oldid=857757128 this diff], no other info.\n\n==West Virginia==\n*[[Blennerhassett Hotel]], Parkersburg, West Virginia.<ref name=Blennerhassett>{{cite web|title=Blennerhassett Hotel |url=https://www.historichotels.org/hotels-resorts/the-blennerhassett-hotel/ |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Wisconsin==\n*[[American Club (Kohler, Wisconsin)|The American Club]] (1918), Kohler, Wisconsin. [[Walter J. Kohler, Sr.]] founded it.  [[Tudor Revival architecture|Tudor]]-style.\n*[[The Edgewater (Madison, Wisconsin)|The Edgewater]] (1948), Madison, Wisconsin.  Art Deco.\n*[[Hilton Milwaukee City Center]] (1928), Milwaukee, Wisconsin, built as the [[Schroeder Hotel]]\n*[[The Pfister Hotel]] (1893), Milwaukee, Wisconsin.  [[Romanesque Revival architecture|Romanesque Revival]]\n\n==Wyoming==\n*[[Old Faithful Inn]] (), [[Yellowstone National Park]], Wyoming\n*[[Lake Yellowstone Hotel & Cabins]] (), [[Yellowstone National Park]], Wyoming\n*[[Sheridan Inn]] (1892), Sheridan, Wyoming\n*[[Alpenhof Lodge]] (), Teton Village, Wyoming\n*[[The Wort Hotel]] (1941), Jackson, Wyoming\n\n==Washington, D.C.==\n*founding: [[Morrison-Clark Historic Inn]] (1864), Washington, D.C.\n*founding: [[The Mayflower Hotel]] (1925)\n*[[Capital Hilton]] (1943), Washington, District of Columbia\n*[[Georgetown Inn]] (1962), Washington, District of Columbia\n*[[Hotel Lombardy]] (1929), Washington, District of Columbia, converted to a hotel in 1994\n*[[Omni Shoreham Hotel]] (1930), Washington DC\n*[[Phoenix Park Hotel]] (1922), Washington, District of Columbia\n*[[Sofitel Washington DC Lafayette Square]] (1925), Washington, District of Columbia, originally designed in [[Art Deco architecture]] by [[Mihran Mesrobian]]\n*[[The Churchill]] (1906).  Or [[The Churchill Hotel]]?  try [[Churchill Hotel]].  [[Beaux Arts architecture]], orginally a luxury apartment building\n*[[The Fairfax at Embassy Row]] (1927), Washington, District of Columbia. Originally \"The Fairfax Hotel\" or \"Fairfax Hotel\"?\n*[[The Graham Georgetown, Tapestry Collection by Hilton]] (1962), Washington, District of Columbia.  try [[The Graham Georgetown]], [[Graham Hotel]], [[The Graham]].  Formerly [[Hotel Monticello]]. Try [[Monticello Hotel]].\n*[[The Henley Park Hotel]] (1918), Washington, District of Columbia.  Is it named after [[Henley Park]] in Oxfordshire?\n*[[The Willard InterContinental, Washington DC]].  [[Beaux Arts architecture]].\n*[[Washington Hilton]] (1965), Washington, District of Columbia\n\n==Puerto Rico==\n*[[Caribe Hilton]], San Juan, Puerto Rico\n*[[Condado Vanderbilt Hotel]] (1919), San Juan, Puerto Rico\n*[[El Convento Hotel]] (1651), San Juan, Puerto Rico, [[Spanish Colonial architecture]]\n*[[The Condado Plaza Hilton]] (1963), San Juan, Puerto Rico, [[International Style (architecture)|International style]]\n\n==U.S. Virgin Islands==\n*[[The Buccaneer (Christiansted, U.S. Virgin Islands)|The Buccaneer]] (1653), Christiansted, U.S. Virgin Islands\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Hotels]]\n[[Category:Hotel affiliation groups]]\n[[Category:National Trust for Historic Preservation]]\n", "name_user": "McGhiever", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMinnesota:Bypass redirect", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Registry_of_the_Historic_Hotels_of_America"}
